When Taiwan's President Chen Shui Bian came to power he promised US
not to rock the status quo ie no provocation such as declaration of
independence.

Now, as more and more corruption allegations surfaced involving CSB
himself and his immediate family, CSB and his party's popularity has
droped to less than 20%. Of the 20% most are hardcore Taiwan
separatists. While the mainstream Taiwanese overwhelmingly supported
the status quo, the extremists firmly believe that if they can provoke
a war, US and Japan will defeat China. This is dispite of the fact
that US State department has repeated warned Taiwan that if they
provoke a war US has the option of not supporting them.
Prsesident CSB in an interview with the BBC claim that US has an
obligation to defend Taiwan. The next day, the state department came
up with a statement saying that the Taiwan Relation act only committ
US &quot;to help Taiwan&quot;.

The latest friction arises from Taiwan's attempt to re-join the UN.
To make it more provocative CSB wanted to use &quot;Taiwan&quot; instead of the
constitutional name of Republic of China.

US can't understand why CSB is doing this as the chance Taiwan gaining
sufficient support internationally is almost zero.
It appears to be designed purely to stire up tension so that US and
Japan can be drawn into a conflict with China.
To add more kick to his provocation CSB wanted to hold a referendom.
In the last two weeks US State Department has spoken twice opposing
such a refendom.
IMO, Bush is getting very annoyed with CSB for 3 reasons.
1) US was never consulted prior to all these provocative act.
2) CSB and his extremists supporters came out one by one claiming that
US will back them up.
3)CSB appears to be playing US domestic politics with Bush, hiring
people to buy support in the Congress to pressure Bush.
(So far Bush's neocon allies are silent).
