SubPrime real estate lending in the US, this time around in home mortgages,
unlike the early 80s, when the problem was over-lending on commercial real
estate, was generated by a natural phenomena contributed to by all those
Asian savers (adding the massive inflow of US capital into &quot;money&quot; funds as
opposed to the usually more attractive equity markets.

Incidentally, with US personal savings and family assets at all time highs,
it's bit short sighted to accuse USAians of not saving.  The problem exists
in the bottom 60% or so of the economic ladder, household whose incomes are
so low as to discourage savings, and by the US tax laws which award holders
of &quot;big&quot; mortgages with subtantial tax benefits.

Meanwhile, with &quot;money&quot; funds glutted, usually wiser heads began to pour
money into the coffers of single family real estate lenders, the only
available loans.  Soon, the lenders were cutting corners to make larger and
more marginal loans, the only way to get the extra funds &quot;in play&quot; and
earning.

Who is at fault?  Well, obviously, the lenders, but no less so the Asian and
other institutuional investors/speculators who knowingly poured funds into
marginal markets.  Were I a Chinese who had lost big money, unable to skowly
dismember my broker who advised the investment, I would change brokerage
houses/trust departments.

In US lending history, the current blip is almost unnoticeable compared to
the &quot;Rolling Thunder&quot; of the collapse of US the savings and loan industry
and the shock waves that caused banks across the US to be
reorganized/merged/assimiliated/just flat shut down....a period in which
real estate used as collateral was often liquidated at less than 25% of
&quot;Loan Value&quot;.  Worst Case estimates and actual real estate market
performance suggest that few loans will result in lender losses exceeding
20%, and even that projection is minimalized by a comparison of actual
interest rates between the two &quot;crunches&quot;.  In the early 80s a
&quot;non-performing&quot; loan with a rate of 12-18%, common commercial mortagage
yields of the time meant not only a loss of collateral value, but a major
loss of interest revenue.  In today's market, with rates about half the
numbers from the early 80s, lender exposure is substantially less.

Simple facts like those are what stimulates smart bankers like those in the
Giannini's old immigrant bank, the BofA, to put 2 billion into a quivering
mortagage lender, Countrywide.  BoA's 2 billion very quickly doubles to
represent about 4 billion in equity position in a company with a
substantially performing portfolio and a modest number of non-performing or
potentially non-performing loans, at worst collateralized at about 80% of
&quot;quick&quot; market value and principally located in medium to high dollar
suburbs of major cities.

